<section class="py-24 px-6">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <!-- Letter format -->
    <div class="letter">
      <div class="letter-header">
        <div class="letter-avatar">
          <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="text-theme-accent">
            <path d="M20 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H8a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"/>
            <circle cx="12" cy="7" r="4"/>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="letter-from">From the builder</p>
          <p class="letter-subtitle">Why this exists</p>
        </div>
        <div class="letter-date">
          <span class="date-dot"></span>
          Written while building inside Molt Code
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="letter-body">
        <p>
          I started using Claude Code on day one. Pretty quickly I was hacking together tmux scripts to run multiple agents in parallel &mdash; one on the frontend, one on the backend. It worked, sort of. But finding old conversations was painful, setup disappeared on restart, and orphan MCP processes would silently eat RAM.
        </p>

        <p>
          So I built Molt Code. Just a place to chat, search, and keep things organized.
        </p>

        <p>
          Then it grew. I needed <strong>context isolation</strong> across projects. Persistent state that survived reboots. A single app that doesn&apos;t spin up duplicate processes.
        </p>

        <p>
          And then the real question hit: what if the agents could manage themselves? What if I could write a spec and have agents plan the work, create the issues, and resolve them in order? That&apos;s what the pipeline does &mdash; and I use it every day.
        </p>

        <p>
          I knew Anthropic and OpenAI would ship their own versions &mdash; and they did. And a wave of VSCode forks arrived with AI bolted on. But those products serve the general public. <strong>This is purpose-built for the workflow I actually have:</strong> orchestrating agents across repos, every day.
        </p>

        <p>
          I use Molt Code daily. I&apos;m building the next version of this app <em>inside</em> this app. It&apos;s sticking around because I need it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="letter-footer">
        <div class="letter-meta">
          <div class="meta-item">
            <span class="meta-label">Status</span>
            <span class="meta-value">Used daily across multiple projects</span>
          </div>
          <div class="meta-item">
            <span class="meta-label">Stability</span>
            <span class="meta-value">Early &mdash; you <em>will</em> find bugs</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <a href="https://github.com/moltcode/moltcode/issues" target="_blank" class="report-link">
